African universities are exploring ways to deepen online learning on the continent in line with global trends. This formed the core of the four-day workshop by the Association of African Universities (AAU) which began Monday at the University of Abuja. The workshop, which has in attendance participants from African countries and Nigeria, has the theme “Online Teaching And Learning Management’. The University of Abuja hosted the event. Declaring the workshop open, the Vice Chancellor, University of Abuja, Prof. Michael U. Adikwu, said the essence of the workshop organized by the Association of African Universities is to look at the totality of online teaching and learning management and how African universities can take advantage of the online platform to deepen learning. Represented by the Director, Quality Assurance, University of Abuja, Prof. Kareem Airede, the VC also said face to face learning is now inadequate for a university learning experience. “We want to look at the various ways online courses can be offered. This is what is happening globally now. It is no longer face to face teaching alone,” he noted. Commenting, Jephtar Adi-Mensah, Project Manager, Association of African Universities said the AAU is committed to making contribution to quality education in Africa. Scientists plan new method of teaching science, mathematics Varsity lecturers demand trainings on modern technology EU to support African project with N2.1bn Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin